==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mimic
<hw>Mim"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>,

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mimic
<hw>Mim"ic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who imitates or mimics,
especially one who does so for sport; a copyist; a buffoon.</def>
<rj><au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mimic
<hw>Mim"ic</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mimicked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mimicking</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To imitate or ape for sport; to ridicule by
imitation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The walk, the words, the gesture, could supply,⟦br⟧
The habit <qex>mimic</qex>, and the mien belie.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>To assume a resemblance to (some
other organism of a totally different nature, or some surrounding
object), as a means of protection or advantage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To ape; imitate; counterfeit; mock.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimically</ent>⟦br⟧
